<HEADLINE>
<P>
REDUCING NICOTINE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DR. NEIL SOLOMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Question: I see where one of the leading cigarette companies is coming out with 
a cigarette that has practically no nicotine, just the way decaffeinated coffee 
has no caffeine. 
</P>
<P>
Do you see anything wrong from a health standpoint with these cigarettes? 
</P>
<P>
Answer: I think it's very revealing that the cigarette company emphasizes the 
low level of nicotine in its product, but says nothing about the level of tar. 
Tar is a major cause of lung cancer and heart disease. Presenting 
"de-nicotined" cigarettes as a safe alternative to regular cigarettes may be a 
good advertising ploy, but it's not honest. 
</P>
<P>
If you have a medical question, write to Neil Solomon MD, P.O. Box 36184, 
Baltimore, Md. 21286-6184. 
</P>
</TEXT>
