<HEADLINE>
<P>
KID BEAT: SHARON, LOIS AND BRAM: FUN FOR ALL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DON SHIRLEY, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Young kids love Sharon, Lois and Bram. The Canadian trio was a big hit at the 
Wiltern Theatre Sunday, and the festivities continue at the Orange County 
Performing Arts Center tonight . 
</P>
<P>
But enough about the kids. What about the parents who have to pay for and sit 
through the concerts? 
</P>
<P>
No problem. Sharon, Lois and Bram are fun for the grown-ups too. 
</P>
<P>
In concert, the trio -- perhaps best known as the stars of "The Elephant Show" 
on cable TV's Nickelodeon -- offers the contrasts that simply come from being a 
trio, as opposed to the male solo acts that dominate the major leagues of the 
children's concert circuit. This group doesn't just sing, it harmonizes. 
</P>
<P>
Bram's low-key wit keeps the parents amused. Sharon and Lois are perky but 
never precious. And if the women begin to seem interchangeable, they've 
eliminated the confusion in concert by wearing sweaters bearing their initials 
-- and explaining that short-haired Sharon's initial also stands for "short" 
and long-haired Lois' initial also stands for "long," while bald and bearded 
Bram's initial also stands for . . . "beard." 
</P>
<P>
Details like this mean a lot in a children's concert. 
</P>
<P>
The musical arrangements in concert are not quite as rich and sophisticated as 
on the group's recordings, but the five-piece band is composed of pros, and the 
variety of musical sources remains admirably eclectic. 
</P>
<P>
The group gets the audience moving without putting any particular child on the 
spot, and they insert a plug for UNICEF as well as one for their TV show. While 
the kids in the back may not be able to see what's happening very well, those 
farther up in the hall will get a kick out of seeing these charming electronic 
images spring to life. 
</P>
<P>
 At Orange County Performing Arts Center, Costa Mesa, tonight at 7. Tickets: 
$8-11; (714) 740-2000 or (213) 480-3232. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Sharon, from left, Lois and Bram combine music and low-key wit to keep 
kids and parents entertained. LORI SHEPLER / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
