<P>
SUCCESS 'A BURDEN' TO MCFERRIN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Service Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
BILLINGS, Mont. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Success can have its drawbacks, says singer and Grammy award winner Bobby 
McFerrin. 
</P>
<P>
"It can be a burden," the soft-spoken McFerrin said. "People want you to repeat 
what you've already done. You have to watch that you keep growing, stretching. 
</P>
<P>
"I found myself getting bored," the San Francisco-based singer said. "I'd begun 
to pander to the audience -- they wanted 'Don't Worry, Be Happy' and 'The 
Wizard of Oz.' It was all getting too easy." 
</P>
<P>
McFerrin and his 11-person all-vocal ensemble "Voicestra" are here preparing 
for a sold-out concert Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
"Don't Worry, Be Happy," was McFerrin's 1989 Grammy hit. 
</P>
